    <h1>Unit 9: Globalization</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">c. 1900 – present &nbsp;|&nbsp; <span class="weighting-badge">Exam Weight: 8–10%</span></p>
 
    <!-- OVERVIEW -->
    <div class="overview-box">
      <h3 style="margin-top:0;">🌐 Unit Overview</h3>
      <p>
        Since 1900 — and especially since 1991 — the world has been more deeply interconnected than ever
        before. New technologies (computers, the internet, mobile phones, airliners, containerized
        shipping) have collapsed distances. International institutions (UN, WHO, WTO, IMF, EU) have tried
        to govern shared problems. Global popular culture, from Hollywood to K-pop, crosses borders with
        unprecedented speed. But globalization has also produced <strong>backlash</strong>:
        environmental crises, pandemics, inequality, religious and nationalist movements, migration
        conflicts, and resistance to Western cultural dominance.
      </p>
      <p style="margin-bottom:0;">
        <strong>Big question:</strong> How have technological, economic, cultural, and environmental
        globalization since 1900 reshaped human life — and what resistance has that change provoked?
      </p>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TIMELINE -->
    <h2>🗓️ Unit 9 Timeline</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1903:</span> Wright brothers' <strong>first powered flight</strong>.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1918–19:</span> <strong>Global influenza pandemic</strong> kills 50–100 million.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1928:</span> <strong>Penicillin</strong> discovered (Fleming); widely used by the 1940s.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1940s–60s:</span> <strong>Green Revolution</strong> sharply raises crop yields (Borlaug).</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1945:</span> Atomic bombs; <strong>UN</strong> and <strong>Bretton Woods</strong> institutions founded.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1948:</span> <strong>WHO</strong> and <strong>Universal Declaration of Human Rights</strong>.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1957:</span> Sputnik; space age begins.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1962:</span> Rachel Carson's <strong>Silent Spring</strong>.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1969:</span> Apollo 11 lands on the moon; ARPANET prototype.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1973 &amp; 1979:</span> <strong>OPEC oil shocks</strong> reshape global economy.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1980:</span> WHO declares <strong>smallpox eradicated</strong>.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1981:</span> AIDS first clinically identified; global epidemic follows.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1989–91:</span> Fall of Soviet bloc; <strong>World Wide Web</strong> proposed (Berners-Lee, 1989).</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1992:</span> <strong>Rio Earth Summit</strong>; Maastricht Treaty creates the European Union.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1994:</span> NAFTA takes effect; Rwanda genocide; Mandela elected in South Africa.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">1995:</span> <strong>WTO</strong> replaces GATT.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">2001:</span> <strong>9/11 attacks</strong>; U.S. "War on Terror" begins.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">2008:</span> <strong>Global financial crisis</strong>.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">2011:</span> <strong>Arab Spring</strong> uprisings.</div>
      <div class="timeline-event"><span class="timeline-date">2020:</span> <strong>COVID-19 pandemic</strong> reshapes work, travel, and politics worldwide.</div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.1 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.1 — Advances in Technology and Exchange after 1900</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-tech">
      <h3>💻 Shrinking the Globe</h3>
 
      <figure class="photo">
        <img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Container_ship_MSC_FABIENNE.jpg?width=700" alt="Container ship MSC Fabienne" />
        <figcaption>A modern <strong>container ship</strong>. Standardized shipping containers (from the 1950s) dramatically reduced the cost and time of global trade, a defining driver of late-20th-century globalization.</figcaption>
      </figure>
 
      <h4>Transportation Revolutions</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Aviation</strong>: Wright brothers (1903) → commercial jetliners (from the 1950s) → mass international tourism and business travel.</li>
        <li><strong>Containerization</strong>: standardized steel containers (1956 onward) cut shipping costs by roughly 90%.</li>
        <li><strong>Highway and rail</strong>: U.S. Interstate system (1956), Japanese Shinkansen (1964), European high-speed rail.</li>
        <li><strong>Pipelines</strong>: transport of oil and gas across continents.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Energy and Materials</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Petroleum</strong> became the world's dominant energy source in the 20th century.</li>
        <li><strong>Nuclear energy</strong> (from the 1950s) — civilian reactors and weapons.</li>
        <li>New materials: plastics, synthetic fibers, semiconductors.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Communications Revolution</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Radio and television</strong> created mass audiences.</li>
        <li><strong>Satellites</strong> (from 1957) enabled global TV and phone links.</li>
        <li><strong>Personal computers</strong> (1970s), the <strong>World Wide Web</strong> (1989), and <strong>mobile phones</strong> (especially smartphones, after 2007) drove a new communications revolution.</li>
        <li>By 2020s, more than half the world's population was online; real-time communication across continents became commonplace.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Agriculture and Biotechnology</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Green Revolution</strong> (1940s–60s): Norman Borlaug's high-yield wheat and rice, synthetic fertilizers, pesticides, and irrigation transformed world food production — especially in Mexico, India, and the Philippines.</li>
        <li><strong>Genetic engineering</strong> (from the 1970s); <strong>CRISPR</strong> gene editing (after 2012).</li>
        <li>Human Genome Project completed (2003).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.2 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.2 — Technological Advances and Limitations: Disease</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-disease">
      <h3>🦠 Triumphs and New Threats</h3>
 
      <h4>Medical Triumphs</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Vaccines</strong>: mass vaccination campaigns against polio (from 1955), measles, hepatitis, smallpox.</li>
        <li><strong>Antibiotics</strong>: penicillin (1928; mass-produced 1940s) transformed treatment of bacterial disease.</li>
        <li><strong>Smallpox eradicated</strong> (WHO declaration, 1980) — the only infectious human disease fully eradicated to date.</li>
        <li>Rising <strong>life expectancy</strong>: global average from ~30 years in 1900 to ~72 by the 2020s.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Pandemics and Epidemics</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1918 influenza pandemic</strong>: killed 50–100 million worldwide (spread partly by WWI troop movements).</li>
        <li><strong>HIV/AIDS</strong>: identified 1981; devastating impact on sub-Saharan Africa; ~40 million deaths by the 2020s; antiretroviral therapy has made it a manageable chronic disease in many places.</li>
        <li><strong>Malaria and tuberculosis</strong> remained major killers, disproportionately affecting the Global South.</li>
        <li><strong>Ebola</strong>: outbreaks in West Africa (2014–16) and Congo.</li>
        <li><strong>COVID-19</strong> (from 2019): first global pandemic of the social-media age; ~7 million recorded deaths; massive economic and social disruption; rapid mRNA vaccine development.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Diseases of Affluence</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Rise of non-infectious diseases: <strong>heart disease</strong>, <strong>diabetes</strong>, and <strong>cancers</strong> linked to smoking, diet, pollution, and longer lifespans.</li>
        <li>Obesity rates rose sharply in high-income and many middle-income countries after 1980.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Limits of Technology</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Unequal access: poorer countries suffer more from preventable diseases.</li>
        <li>Rise of <strong>antibiotic resistance</strong>.</li>
        <li>Ethical debates over vaccination, genetic engineering, and end-of-life care.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.3 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.3 — Debates about the Environment after 1900</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-environ">
      <h3>🌍 The Planet Under Strain</h3>
 
      <figure class="photo">
        <img src="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Special:FilePath/Earthrise.jpg?width=600" alt="Earthrise, Apollo 8, 1968" />
        <figcaption><strong>Earthrise</strong> by Apollo 8 astronaut William Anders (24 December 1968). The image became iconic for the modern environmental movement, visualizing Earth as a fragile, interconnected whole.</figcaption>
      </figure>
 
      <h4>Environmental Pressures</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Population growth</strong>: from ~1.6 billion (1900) to ~8 billion (2022).</li>
        <li><strong>Urbanization</strong>: over half the world lived in cities by ~2008.</li>
        <li><strong>Deforestation</strong>: Amazon, Southeast Asia, Central Africa.</li>
        <li><strong>Pollution</strong>: air (smog, acid rain), water, ocean plastic.</li>
        <li><strong>Overfishing</strong>, soil depletion, biodiversity loss ("sixth extinction" debate).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Climate Change</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Greenhouse gas emissions</strong> from fossil fuels have caused measurable global warming since the mid-20th century.</li>
        <li>Effects: rising sea levels, shrinking ice caps and glaciers, more intense storms and wildfires, shifting agricultural zones.</li>
        <li>Disproportionate impact on poorer, low-lying, or drought-prone regions (Bangladesh, Pacific islands, the Sahel).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Environmental Movement</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Rachel Carson's <em>Silent Spring</em> (1962) — catalyst for modern environmentalism.</li>
        <li><strong>Earth Day</strong> (from 1970); <strong>Greenpeace</strong> (1971).</li>
        <li>Rise of NGOs: WWF, Sierra Club, 350.org.</li>
        <li>Youth movements in the 21st century (e.g., Greta Thunberg and Fridays for Future).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>International Agreements</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stockholm Conference</strong> (1972) — first major UN environment conference.</li>
        <li><strong>Montreal Protocol</strong> (1987) — successfully phased down ozone-depleting chemicals.</li>
        <li><strong>Rio Earth Summit</strong> (1992).</li>
        <li><strong>Kyoto Protocol</strong> (1997) and <strong>Paris Agreement</strong> (2015) — emissions reductions commitments.</li>
        <li>Debates: "common but differentiated responsibilities" — should wealthy industrial emitters pay more?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.4 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.4 — Economics in the Global Age</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-econ">
      <h3>💰 Markets Without Borders</h3>
 
      <h4>Rise of Neoliberal Globalization</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>From the 1970s–80s, major powers shifted toward <strong>neoliberalism</strong>: free trade, privatization, deregulation, reduced social spending (Thatcher in the UK, Reagan in the U.S., Pinochet in Chile).</li>
        <li><strong>WTO</strong> (1995, succeeding GATT) lowered tariffs and pushed open markets.</li>
        <li>Regional blocs: <strong>European Union</strong> (1993; euro 1999), <strong>NAFTA</strong> (1994; replaced by USMCA 2020), <strong>ASEAN</strong>, Mercosur, African Union.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Global Financial Markets</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Multinational corporations (MNCs)</strong>: Royal Dutch Shell, Walmart, Toyota, Apple, Samsung.</li>
        <li>Massive <strong>foreign direct investment</strong>, capital flows, and 24-hour financial markets.</li>
        <li><strong>Offshoring</strong> of manufacturing from high-wage to lower-wage economies (U.S./Japan → China, Mexico, Vietnam).</li>
        <li>Rise of <strong>supply chains</strong> like Apple's (U.S. design, Taiwanese chips, Chinese assembly).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Rise of New Economic Powers</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>China</strong>'s post-1978 reforms produced the largest sustained economic boom in history; by the 2010s, the world's second-largest economy.</li>
        <li><strong>India</strong>'s 1991 liberalization; tech services boom (Bengaluru/Bangalore).</li>
        <li><strong>BRICS</strong> (Brazil, Russia, India, China, South Africa, later expanded) reshaped global economic geography.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Crises and Inequality</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>1973 and 1979 oil shocks</strong> — OPEC leverage reshaped energy politics.</li>
        <li><strong>1980s debt crisis</strong> in Latin America and Africa led to IMF/World Bank <strong>structural adjustment</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>1997 Asian financial crisis</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>2008 global financial crisis</strong>: U.S. housing and banking collapse triggered a global recession and new regulations.</li>
        <li>Rising <strong>inequality within countries</strong>, even as inequality between some countries narrowed.</li>
        <li><strong>Precarious labor</strong>: gig economy, contract work, informal sector.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.5 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.5 — Calls for Reform and Responses after 1900</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-reform">
      <h3>📣 Expanding Rights and Dignity</h3>
 
      <h4>Human Rights Movements</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Universal Declaration of Human Rights</strong> (1948) set a new vocabulary of universal rights.</li>
        <li><strong>NGOs</strong>: Amnesty International (1961), Human Rights Watch (1978), Médecins Sans Frontières (1971).</li>
        <li>Expansion of rights discourse to gender, race, sexuality, disability, children.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Women's Rights</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Women's suffrage spread across the 20th century — from New Zealand (1893) and the U.S. (1920) to Saudi municipal elections (2015).</li>
        <li><strong>UN women's conferences</strong> (Mexico City 1975, Beijing 1995).</li>
        <li>Ongoing struggles: reproductive rights, violence against women, wage gaps, educational access, female political leadership.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Racial Equality and Decolonization of Knowledge</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>U.S. Civil Rights Movement; South African anti-apartheid; indigenous land rights.</li>
        <li><strong>Black Lives Matter</strong> (from 2013): global movement against police violence and structural racism.</li>
        <li>Calls to "decolonize" universities, museums, and cultural institutions.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>LGBTQ+ Rights</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Stonewall riots</strong> (1969) launched the modern gay-rights movement.</li>
        <li>Decriminalization and recognition of same-sex marriage in many countries (Netherlands 2001; Argentina 2010; U.S. 2015; Taiwan 2019).</li>
        <li>Backlash and continued criminalization in other states.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Labor Movements</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Industrial unions became a major force in the early-to-mid 20th century (AFL-CIO, Cosatu, Solidarity).</li>
        <li>Declining union density in many high-income countries after 1980.</li>
        <li>New struggles: "Fight for $15," gig-worker organizing, farmworker movements (César Chávez and UFW).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.6 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.6 — Globalized Culture after 1900</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-culture">
      <h3>🎬 A Shared Cultural Marketplace</h3>
 
      <h4>Mass Culture Goes Global</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Hollywood</strong> became the world's most influential film industry from the 1920s.</li>
        <li><strong>Television</strong> and then <strong>streaming platforms</strong> (Netflix, Disney+) homogenized and diversified global viewing.</li>
        <li><strong>Music</strong>: jazz, blues, rock (Elvis, Beatles), hip-hop, Latin pop, Afrobeats, K-pop (BTS, BLACKPINK).</li>
        <li><strong>Sports</strong>: FIFA World Cup and the Olympics as massive global spectacles.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Consumer Culture</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Global brands: Coca-Cola, Nike, McDonald's, Apple, Samsung, Toyota.</li>
        <li>Fashion and food globalized (sushi in Kansas; pizza in Shanghai; Starbucks in 80+ countries).</li>
        <li>Concept of "<strong>McDonaldization</strong>" (George Ritzer) — standardization, efficiency, predictability.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Cultural Hybridity</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Global flows produced fusions: Bollywood blending Indian classical forms with Hollywood conventions; reggaeton's mix of Latin, Caribbean, and hip-hop.</li>
        <li>Migration built multicultural cities: London, Toronto, São Paulo, Singapore, Dubai.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Religion in a Global Age</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Continued global growth of <strong>Christianity</strong> in Africa, Latin America, and Asia; evangelical and Pentecostal movements surged.</li>
        <li><strong>Islamic revival</strong> from the late 20th century (Iranian Revolution, Muslim Brotherhood, Salafism).</li>
        <li><strong>New religious movements</strong>, spiritual pluralism, and growing "nones" (religiously unaffiliated) in Europe and North America.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Digital Culture</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Social media (from the 2000s) reshaped politics, protest, and identity.</li>
        <li>"Viral" phenomena, memes, and influencer culture.</li>
        <li>Simultaneously enabled <strong>disinformation</strong>, polarization, and new forms of authoritarian control (Great Firewall of China, state surveillance).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.7 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.7 — Resistance to Globalization after 1900</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-resist">
      <h3>🛑 Globalization's Discontents</h3>
 
      <h4>Economic Resistance</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Anti-globalization protests</strong>: Seattle WTO protests (1999), Genoa G8 (2001).</li>
        <li><strong>Labor opposition</strong>: unions in high-income countries resisted offshoring and free-trade deals (e.g., opposition to NAFTA).</li>
        <li>Rise of <strong>populist protectionism</strong> in the 2010s (Trump's tariffs, Brexit).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Religious Fundamentalism and Violence</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Islamist extremism</strong>: al-Qaeda (from 1988), 9/11 attacks (2001), ISIS (2014), Boko Haram.</li>
        <li>Hindu nationalism in India (BJP); Buddhist-nationalist violence against Muslims in Myanmar.</li>
        <li>Christian nationalism in parts of Europe and the Americas.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Political Backlash</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Rise of <strong>right-wing populism</strong>: Hungary's Orbán, India's Modi, the U.S. under Trump, Bolsonaro in Brazil, far-right parties in the EU.</li>
        <li><strong>Brexit</strong> (2016, implemented 2020) — UK voted to leave the European Union.</li>
        <li>Authoritarian turns: Putin's Russia, Erdoğan's Turkey, Xi Jinping's centralization in China.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Cultural Resistance</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Protection of <strong>indigenous languages and knowledge</strong>.</li>
        <li>"<strong>Slow Food</strong>" movement (Italy, 1986) against fast-food globalization.</li>
        <li>French cultural defense of its language and film industry against U.S. dominance.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Environmental and Social Justice Movements</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Indigenous resistance to oil pipelines (Standing Rock, 2016).</li>
        <li>Climate strikes (Fridays for Future, 2018–).</li>
        <li>Global <strong>#MeToo</strong> and <strong>Black Lives Matter</strong> movements mobilized online across borders.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.8 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.8 — Institutions Developing in a Globalized World</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-inst">
      <h3>🏛️ Governing a Smaller Planet</h3>
 
      <h4>The United Nations System</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Security Council</strong> (P5: U.S., UK, France, China, Russia) with veto power.</li>
        <li><strong>General Assembly</strong>: 193 member states.</li>
        <li>Specialized agencies: <strong>WHO</strong>, <strong>UNESCO</strong>, <strong>UNICEF</strong>, <strong>UNHCR</strong>.</li>
        <li>UN peacekeeping missions ("blue helmets") since the Suez Crisis (1956).</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Economic Institutions</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>IMF</strong> and <strong>World Bank</strong> (1944 Bretton Woods).</li>
        <li><strong>WTO</strong> (1995, from GATT) — manages rules of global trade.</li>
        <li><strong>G7</strong>, <strong>G20</strong> — coordinating bodies of major economies.</li>
        <li><strong>OPEC</strong> (1960) — oil exporters' cartel.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Regional Organizations</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>European Union</strong>: shared market, single currency (euro), common foreign-policy machinery.</li>
        <li><strong>African Union</strong> (2002, succeeding OAU 1963).</li>
        <li><strong>ASEAN</strong>, Mercosur, Arab League.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Humanitarian and NGO Networks</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Red Cross/Red Crescent.</li>
        <li>Médecins Sans Frontières / Doctors Without Borders.</li>
        <li>Amnesty International, Oxfam, Save the Children.</li>
        <li>Gates Foundation and other mega-philanthropies.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>New Security Challenges</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Terrorism</strong> and counterterrorism.</li>
        <li><strong>Cybersecurity</strong> and cyberwarfare.</li>
        <li>Return of <strong>great-power competition</strong>: U.S.–China, Russia's 2014 annexation of Crimea and 2022 invasion of Ukraine.</li>
        <li>Climate-driven migration and conflict.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Tensions within Global Governance</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>UN Security Council vetoes often paralyze responses (Syria, Ukraine).</li>
        <li>Critics argue that existing institutions over-represent 1945 power balances and under-represent the Global South.</li>
        <li>Regional and bilateral arrangements increasingly bypass global institutions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
    <!-- TOPIC 9.9 -->
    <h2>Topic 9.9 — Continuity and Change in a Globalized World</h2>
    <div class="region-card region-causation">
      <h3>🔄 Synthesizing Unit 9 and the Course</h3>
 
      <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
        <table class="compare-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Domain</th>
              <th>Continuity (1200 → present)</th>
              <th>Change (esp. 1900 → present)</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Trade</strong></td><td>Long-distance exchange persists (Silk Roads → container ships)</td><td>Volume, speed, and complexity grew enormously; digital trade</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Disease</strong></td><td>Pandemics spread along trade networks</td><td>Modern medicine extended lifespan; new threats (HIV, COVID)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Environment</strong></td><td>Human impact on landscapes is ancient</td><td>Global-scale, anthropogenic climate change</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Power</strong></td><td>Strong states &amp; empires shape the world</td><td>Superpowers, NGOs, MNCs, and digital platforms share power</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Culture</strong></td><td>Cross-cultural exchange (e.g., Islamic world; Columbian Exchange)</td><td>Real-time global media; hybrid global pop culture</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Rights</strong></td><td>Status hierarchies (gender, race, class) widespread</td><td>Universal human rights framework; ongoing struggle for equality</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Migration</strong></td><td>People have always moved (nomadic, slavery, labor)</td><td>Mass air travel, refugees, diasporas, digital nomads</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
 
      <h4>Major Continuities from the Whole Course</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Interconnectedness</strong> has deepened across every period — from post-classical trade networks to the internet.</li>
        <li><strong>Disease, migration, and environmental change</strong> travel along exchange networks; their scale has grown.</li>
        <li><strong>State-building</strong> remains a key political project — even as the forms (empires, nation-states, regional blocs) change.</li>
        <li><strong>Inequalities</strong> — of wealth, gender, and race — endure in new forms.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Major Changes</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Scale and speed</strong>: today's flows of information, capital, people, and disease dwarf those of earlier periods.</li>
        <li><strong>Anthropocene</strong>: humans are now the dominant force shaping the planetary environment.</li>
        <li><strong>Human rights framework</strong>: universalist rights discourse is a 20th-century innovation.</li>
        <li><strong>Decline of formal empire</strong>: near-universal norm of sovereign nation-states.</li>
        <li><strong>Rise of new powers</strong>: China's re-emergence and the shifting U.S.–China rivalry are defining forces of the early 21st century.</li>
      </ul>
 
      <h4>Open Questions for the Future</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Can international institutions adapt fast enough to climate change, pandemics, and AI?</li>
        <li>Will democracy, authoritarianism, or hybrid systems dominate the 21st century?</li>
        <li>How will nations manage the trade-offs between openness, security, and equality?</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
 
